text: CLAIM: Cognitive biases can lead to superficial problem-solving in fast-paced environments.
CLAIM: Focusing on root causes can lead to more effective and cost-efficient outcomes.
CLAIM: The 'zone of average' exists, where conditions are sufficient enough to discourage further improvement.
CLAIM: Human behavior can be influenced by group norms to maintain the status quo.
CLAIM: Inertia can be harnessed as a force for good when aligned with personal goals.
CLAIM: Behavioral changes are more effective through environmental modification than through sheer effort.
CLAIM: External rewards are optional and not necessary for achieving best performance.
CLAIM: Self-judgment is more impactful than any external judgment.
CLAIM: Self-serving bias is a psychological tendency to attribute success to internal factors and failure to external ones.
CLAIM: Excuses are often self-focused and do not address root causes.
CLAIM: Acceptance leads to identifying solutions
CLAIM: Self-knowledge encompasses recognizing cognitive blind spots and personal defaults
CLAIM: Persistent repetition of minor mistakes results in eventual failure due to cumulative negative effects
CLAIM: Cognitive biases are innate and evolved for survival, but can lead to suboptimal decisions.
CLAIM: Blind spots, including perceptual and cognitive limitations, are common in human decision-making and can be managed through structured approaches.
CLAIM: The environment determines which behavioral paths are easier
